               <history>
                  <origin>Unsigned but possibly completed in either in Safavid <origPlace
                        cert="medium" ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000235">Iran</origPlace>
                     or Mughal <origPlace cert="medium"
                        ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7024418">India</origPlace> before the
                     death of the Mughal artist <persName role="fmo asn"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/254625827" key="person_254625827">Miskīn (fl.
                        1580–1604)</persName> as per a notation on folio <locus from="1a" to="1a"
                        >1a</locus>.</origin>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquisitioned by the royal Mughal library sometime
                        during the reign of <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/38320916" key="person_38320916">Jahāngīr (b.
                           1569, r. 1605–27)</persName>, then his son <addName
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/13108102" key="person_13108102">Prince
                           Khurrām</addName>, whom later ruled as the Emperor <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/13108102"
                           key="person_13108102">Shāh Jahān (b. 1592 r.
                     1628–58)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Evidently given to the latter's son, Prince <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/27879596"
                           key="person_27879596">Dārā Shikūh (1615–59)</persName>, but then shortly
                        before his execution, confiscated by his brother <persName type="standard"
                           role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/6178410/" key="person_6178410"
                           >‘Ālamgīr I (b. 1618, r. 1658–1707)</persName>, whom then presented it to
                        his sister, <persName type="standard" role="fmo" key="person_f6528"
                           >Rawshan-Ārā (1617–1671)</persName>, and thereafter passed on to other
                        Mughal elites. </p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Possibly the same volume acquired by British travel writer
                           <persName cert="medium" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/2344700"
                           key="person_2344700">Henry Swinburne (1743–1803)</persName>, who sold his
                        library through <orgName role="auc" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/133731879"
                           key="person_133731879">Leigh, Sotheby, &amp; Son</orgName> on <date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1803-01-10">10 Jan. 1803</date>, including a
                        manuscript described in the catalgoue as <quote xml:lang="en">...<hi
                              rend="italic">a very splendid and beautiful copy</hi>, 4to. N. B. It
                           appears to have been procured from the Imperial Library at Delhi, the
                           Seal of several Prince being affixed to it.</quote></p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance><p>While unsigned, the English description of the volume on folio
                           <locus from="1a" to="1a">1a</locus> closely compares with the hand of
                           <persName cert="high" type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/viaf/44733962/" key="person_44733962">Sir Gore
                           Ouseley (1770–84)</persName>.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Subsequently acquired by Methodist theologian <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/120696480" key="person_120696480">Adam Clarke
                           (1762–1832)</persName>, then sold by his son <persName role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/79253656" key="person_79253656">Joseph
                           Butterworth Bulmer Clarke (d. 1855)</persName> in 1836, listed as no. 129
                        in his catalogue. However, this volume does not appear in subsequent sale
                        catalogues for his collection.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance><p>Evidently acquired and then sold by <placeName
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7010597">Liverpool</placeName>
                        bookseller <persName type="standard" role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/193147423155044882200"
                           key="person_193147423155044882200">Thomas Kaye (1780–1865) </persName>;
                        however, the exact circumanstances remain unclear.</p></provenance>
                  <provenance>
                     <p>Subsequently obtained by scholar <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/" key="person_20108923">Nathaniel
                           Bland (1803–1865)</persName> after whose death, <placeName type="city"
                           ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7011781">London</placeName>
                        bookseller <persName type="standard" role="bsl"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/5679225/" key="person_5679225">Bernard Quaritch
                           (1819–1899)</persName> sold his oriental manuscripts to <persName
                           type="standard" role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/"
                           key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of Crawford
                           (1812–1880)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1866"
                           >1866</date>.</p>
                  </provenance>
                  <provenance>Purchased by <persName type="standard" role="dnr" key="person_f6379"
                        >Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian"
                        when="1901">1901</date> from <persName type="standard" role="fmo"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/" key="person_9985420">James Ludovic
                        Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847–1913)</persName>. </provenance>
                  <acquisition>
                     <p>Bequeathed by <persName type="standard" key="person_f6379">Enriqueta Rylands
                           (1843–1908)</persName> in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908"
                           >1908</date> to the <orgName type="corporation" role="rps"
                           ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/312795145/">John Rylands Library</orgName>.</p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>
